"Nehring S., Hesse K.-J.","Invasive alien plants in marine protected areas: The Spartina anglica affair in the European Wadden Sea",2008,"Biological Invasions","10","6",,"937","950",,,10.1007/s10530-008-9244-z,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-46649100256&partnerID=40&md5=4baa47b384ef6fe99646b876bd8c8cc0","AeT Umweltplanung, Bismarckstraße 19, 56068 Koblenz, Germany; Forschungs- und Technologiezentrum Westküste, Universität Kiel, Hafentörn, 25746 Büsum, Germany","Nehring, S., AeT Umweltplanung, Bismarckstraße 19, 56068 Koblenz, Germany; Hesse, K.-J., Forschungs- und Technologiezentrum Westküste, Universität Kiel, Hafentörn, 25746 Büsum, Germany","The common cord-grass Spartina anglica, a fertile hybrid of S. maritima and S. alterniflora, was planted in the European Wadden Sea extensively during the late 1920s and 1930s to promote sediment accretion. After establishment, it colonised as a pioneer plant in the upper tidal zone, where it occurs frequently in coherent swards at the seaward front of saltmarshes and in patches on the tidal flats. Often, a conspicuous, almost monotypic, belt of S. anglica is formed. Over the last two decades, an increase in abundance and accelerated spread of S. anglica was observed, possibly promoted by warmer spring temperatures. This alien species may benefit from global warming, and there is considerable concern about its harmful impacts on the native biocoenoses and native biodiversity of the unique Wadden Sea ecosystem, encompassing effects on hydromorphodynamics and coastal protection. For a definitive assessment, however, an adequate quantification and comparison of documented and potential effects of S. anglica is important, but currently unavailable. Consequently, no management strategy exists for the prevention or restoration of the Wadden Sea ecosystem. Thus, the development of an alien species plan on the level of the Trilateral Cooperation on the Protection of the Wadden Sea is essential. © 2008 Springer Science+Business Media B.V.","Black list; Climate change; Europe; Impacts; North Sea; Protected area; Spartina anglica; Wadden Sea","abundance; accretion; biodiversity; colonization; comparative study; environmental restoration; global warming; invasive species; marine park; saltmarsh; seagrass; tidal flat; Atlantic Ocean; Eurasia; Europe; North Sea; Wadden Sea; Spartina anglica",,,,,,"Adsersen, H., Spartina (Vadegræs) i Horsens Fjord (1974) Flora Fauna, 80, pp. 37-42; Angers, D.A., Caron, J., Plant-induced changes in soil structure: Processes and feedbacks (1998) Biogeochemistry, 42, pp. 55-72; Zur Ausbreitung und Gesellschaftsbildung von Spartina townsendii an der Ostfriesischen Küste (1973) Jahresbericht 1972, , Anonymous Forschungsstelle Norderney (ed) Norderney; Chevalier, A., Note sur les Spartina de la flore française (1923) Bull Soc Bot Fr, 70, pp. 54-63; Christiansen, C., Møller, J.T., Rate of establishment and seasonal immersion of Spartina in Mariager Fjord, Denmark (1983) Holarctic Ecol, 6, pp. 315-319; Chung, C.H., Thirty years of ecological engineering with Spartina plantations in China (1993) Ecol Eng, 2, pp. 261-289; Chung, C.H., Forty years of ecological engineering with Spartina plantations in China (2006) Ecol Eng, 27, pp. 49-57; (2003) European Strategy on Invasive Alien Species. Convention on the Conservation of European Wildlife and Natural Habitats (Bern Convention), , Council of Europe. Council of Europe Strasbourg; Corten, A., Van De Kamp, G., Variation in the abundance of southern fish species in the southern North Sea in relation to hydrography and wind (1996) ICES J Mar Sci, 53, pp. 1113-1119; (2006) Schiermonnikoog Declaration - Ministerial Declaration of the Tenth Trilateral Governmental Conference on the Protection of the Wadden Sea, , CWSS. CWSS Wilhelmshaven; De Poorter, M., (2007) Invasive Alien Species and Protected Areas - A Scoping Report, , IUCN Gland Cambridge; Dethier, M.N., Hacker, S.D., (2004) Improving Management Practices for